'''Rennes''' ({{IPA-fr|ʁɛn|-|Fr-Paris--Rennes.ogg}}; {{lang-br|Roazhon}} {{IPA-br|ˈrwɑːzən|}}; [[Gallo language|Gallo]]: ''Resnn''; {{Lang-la|Condate Redonum}}) is a city in the east of [[Brittany]] in northwestern [[France]] at the confluence of the [[Ille]] and the [[Vilaine]]. Rennes is the capital of the [[Brittany (administrative region)|region of Brittany]], as well as the [[Ille-et-Vilaine]] [[Departments of France|department]]. In 2015, the city was [[Urban area (France)|the tenth largest in France]], with a [[metropolitan area]] of about 720,000 inhabitants.&lt;ref&gt;[http://www.insee.fr/fr/themes/document.asp?ref_id=17914#trois] INSEE.fr&lt;/ref&gt; The inhabitants of Rennes are called Rennais(e)(es) in French

Rennes's history goes back more than 2,000 years, at a time when it was a small Gallic village named Condate. Together with [[Vannes]] and [[Nantes]], it was one of the major cities of the ancient [[Duchy of Brittany]]. From the early sixteenth century until the [[French Revolution]], Rennes was a parliamentary, administrative and garrison city of the historic province of [[Brittany]] of the [[Kingdom of France]] as evidenced by its 17th century [[Parliament of Brittany|Parliament's Palace]]. Rennes played an important role in the Stamped Paper Revolt in 1675. After the destructive fire of 1720, the medieval wooden center of the city was partially rebuilt in stone. Remaining mostly [[Rural area|rural]] until the [[World War II|Second World War]], Rennes really developed in the twentieth century. 

Since the 1950s, Rennes has grown in importance through [[rural flight]] and its modern industrial development, partly automotive. The city developed extensive building plans to accommodate upwards of 200,000 inhabitants. During the 1980s, Rennes became one of the main centres in [[telecommunication]] and high technology industry. It is now a significant [[Digital economy|digital]] innovation centre in France. In 2002, Rennes became the smallest city in the world to have a [[Rennes Metro|Metro]] line. 

Labeled a city of art and history, it has preserved an important [[Middle Ages|medieval]] and [[Classical architecture|classical]] heritage within its historic center with over 90 buildings  protected as historic monuments&lt;ref&gt;{{Cite web|title=Ministère de la Culture - Maintenance|url=http://www2.culture.gouv.fr/redir_pop/index.html?ACTION=CHERCHER&amp;FIELD_1=INSEE&amp;DOM=MH&amp;VALUE_1=35238|access-date=2020-10-31|website=www2.culture.gouv.fr}}&lt;/ref&gt;. With more than [[College town|66,000 students]] in 2016, it is also the eighth-largest university campus of France.&lt;ref&gt;[http://cache.media.enseignementsup-recherche.gouv.fr/file/Atlas_2012-2013/27/8/Atlas_1213_Web_316278.pdf]&lt;/ref&gt; . In 2018, ''[[L'Express]]'' named Rennes as &quot;the most liveable city in France&quot;.&lt;ref&gt;[https://www.lexpress.fr/emploi/le-palmares-2018-des-villes-ou-il-fait-bon-vivre-et-travailler_1984924.html]&lt;/ref&gt;

